Access Modifiers

TypeScript provides three access modifiers to control the visibility of class members.

### public

Accessible from anywhere (default if no modifier specified):

```typescript
class User {
  public name: string;

  constructor(name: string) {
    this.name = name;
  }

  public greet(): string {
    return `Hello, ${this.name}`;
  }
}

const user = new User("Alice");
console.log(user.name); // OK
console.log(user.greet()); // OK
```

### private

Accessible only within the declaring class:

```typescript
class BankAccount {
  private balance: number = 0;

  deposit(amount: number): void {
    this.balance += amount; // OK
  }

  getBalance(): number {
    return this.balance; // OK
  }
}

const account = new BankAccount();
// account.balance // Error: Property 'balance' is private
```

### protected

Accessible within the class and its subclasses:

```typescript
class Animal {
  protected dna: string = "secret-code";
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  showDna(): string {
    return this.dna; // OK: protected in subclass
  }
}

const dog = new Dog();
// dog.dna // Error: Property 'dna' is protected
```

### Comparison

| Modifier | Class | Subclass | External |
|----------|-------|----------|----------|
| public | Yes | Yes | Yes |
| protected | Yes | Yes | No |
| private | Yes | No | No |

### ECMAScript Private Fields (#)

```typescript
class MyClass {
  #privateField: number = 42;

  getPrivate(): number {
    return this.#privateField;
  }
}
```

> **Key Point:** TypeScript's `private` is enforced at compile time only. Use ECMAScript `#` private fields for runtime privacy.

codeExample:
class Employee {
  constructor(
    public name: string,
    private salary: number,
    protected department: string
  ) {}

  public getSalary(): number {
    return this.salary;
  }
}

class Manager extends Employee {
  constructor(name: string, salary: number, department: string) {
    super(name, salary, department);
  }

  public getDepartment(): string {
    return this.department;
  }

  public getSalaryInfo(): string {
    return `Manager ${this.name}`;
  }
}
